---
/** Hub: lottery tax, lump sum vs annuity. Worked example by lotteryTax(). */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import LotteryTaxCalculator from '../../components/calculators/LotteryTaxCalculator.tsx';
import { lotteryTax } from '../../lib/gambling';
import { formatMoney } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

const ex = lotteryTax(100000000, 60000000, 0, 'single', 'OH');
---

<Base
  title="Lottery tax calculator 2026 — lump sum vs annuity"
  description="What you keep from a lottery jackpot: the lump-sum cash value versus the 30-year annuity, after 37% federal tax, withholding and state tax."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year</p>
    <h1>Lottery tax calculator</h1>
    <p class="tagline">The advertised jackpot is not the check. Between the cash discount and the top bracket, most of it never arrives.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    A jackpot winner faces two decisions the ticket does not mention: take the lump
    sum (a cash value around 60% of the advertised jackpot, taxed all at once) or
    the 30-year annuity (the full jackpot, taxed as each payment arrives). Either
    way the top 37% federal bracket applies, 24% is withheld up front, and your
    state usually takes a cut too. This shows both take-homes.
  </p>

  <LotteryTaxCalculator client:load />

  <h2>Worked example — a {formatMoney(100000000)} jackpot in Ohio</h2>
  <p>
    A {formatMoney(100000000)} jackpot with a {formatMoney(60000000)} cash value:
  </p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Option</th><th>After-tax total</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Lump sum (cash value, taxed now)</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.lumpSumAfterTax)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>30-year annuity ({formatMoney(ex.annualPayment)}/yr)</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.annuityAfterTaxTotal)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The lump sum leaves {formatMoney(ex.lumpSumAfterTax)} — the {formatMoney(100000000)}
    jackpot became a {formatMoney(60000000)} cash value, then tax took most of the
    rest. The annuity delivers {formatMoney(ex.annuityAfterTaxTotal)} over 30 years:
    more in total, because you skip the cash-value discount and do not cram every
    dollar into one year's top bracket. The lump sum wins only if you can invest it
    to beat that gap.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Lump sum or annuity?</h3>
    <p>
      The annuity almost always yields more after tax — it avoids the cash-value
      haircut and spreads income across years. The lump sum is worth it only if you
      will invest it and earn more than the gap, and if you trust yourself with a
      large sum at once. Most financial advice leans annuity for the discipline;
      most winners take the lump sum anyway.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>How much tax on lottery winnings?</h3>
    <p data-review="legal">
      Federally, lottery winnings are ordinary income, so a jackpot is taxed at the
      top 37% rate. {Math.round(24)}% is withheld up front on the payout, but the
      full 37% is due at filing — so expect a further bill. Then most states tax it
      too, from a few percent to over 10%; a handful of states do not.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Why is the lump sum so much less than the jackpot?</h3>
    <p>
      Two haircuts. First, the "cash value" is what the lottery would have invested
      to fund the 30-year annuity — usually about 60% of the advertised figure.
      Then federal and state tax come off that. A {formatMoney(100000000)} headline
      can become {formatMoney(ex.lumpSumAfterTax)} in hand.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Can I reduce the tax?</h3>
    <p>
      Not much on the winnings themselves — it is ordinary income. Winners sometimes
      use a lottery trust or entity for privacy, spread a group win with a
      documented sharing agreement (to avoid gift tax among the pool), and do heavy
      charitable planning. None of that changes the top-bracket rate on what you keep.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/gambling-tax-calculator/">Gambling tax calculator</a> — winnings and the 90% loss rule</li>
    <li><a href="/w2g-tax-calculator/">W-2G calculator</a> — withholding vs actual tax</li>
    <li><a href="/capital-gains-tax-calculator/">Capital gains calculator</a> — investing a lump sum</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">
    Estimate for the 2026 tax year. The annuity is modeled as equal payments; real
    annuities rise about 5% a year. State tax varies. Not tax or investment advice.
  </p>
</Base>
